45.clickbait: "I can't let you do that, Dave."

48.title: Patch resistance
48.clickbait: One does not simply solve the value alignment problem.

107.clickbait: What we do and don't understand how to do, using unlimited computing power, is a critical distinction and important frontier.

1rt.clickbait: Arbital path is a linear sequence of pages tailored specifically to teach a given concept to a user.

1y.title: Orthogonality Thesis
1y.clickbait: Will smart AIs automatically become benevolent, or automatically become hostile?  Or do different AI designs imply different goals?

2c.title: Advanced agent properties
2c.clickbait: How smart does a machine intelligence need to be, for its niceness to become an issue?  "Advanced" is a broad term to cover cognitive abilities such that we'd need to start considering AI alignment.

2l.title: Advanced safety
2l.clickbait: An agent is *really* safe when it has the capacity to do anything, but chooses to do what the programmer wants.

2v.title: AI alignment
2v.clickbait: The great civilizational problem of creating artificially intelligent computer systems such that running them is a good idea.

2w.title: Edge instantiation
2w.clickbait: When you ask the AI to make people happy, and it tiles the universe with the smallest objects that can be happy.

2x.title: Omnipotence test for AI safety
2x.clickbait: Would your AI produce disastrous outcomes if it suddenly gained omnipotence and omniscience? If so, why did you program something that *wants* to hurt you and is held back only by lacking the power?

3d.title: Arbital
3d.clickbait: Arbital is the place for crowdsourced, intuitive math explanations.

3g.title: List: value-alignment problems
3g.text:
# Foreseen resistant difficulties

 - Value loading
  - Edge instantiation
  - Unforeseen maximums
  - Nearest unblocked neighbors
  - Ontology identification
     - Cartesian boundary
     - Human identification
  - Inductive value learning
     - Ambiguity-querying
  - Moral uncertainty
     - Indifference
 - Corrigibility
  - Anapartistic reasoning
     - Programmer deception
     - Early conservatism
     - Reasoning under confusion
  - User maximization / Unshielded argmax
     - Hypothetical user maximization
 - Genie theory
  - Limited optimization
     - Safe optimization measure (such that we are confident it has no Edge that secretly optimizes more)
           - Factoring of an agent by stage/component optimization power
  - Low-impact AGI
     - Minimum Safe AA (just flip off switch and shut down safely)
     - Safe impact measure
     - Armstrong-style permitted output channels
     - Shutdown utility function
  - Oracle utility function
      - Safe indifference?
  - Effable optimization (opposite of cognitive uncontainability; uses only comprehensible strategies)
  - Online checkability
       - Reporting without programmer maximization
  - Transparency
  - Do What I Know I Mean
 - Superintelligent security (all subproblems placing us in adversarial context vs. other SIs)
  - Bargaining
     - Non-blackmailability
     - First-mover penalty / epistemic low ground advantage
     - Division of gains from trade
  - Epistemic exclusion of distant SIs
     - Christiano's Hack
     - Breaking out of hypotheses
 - 'Philosophical' problems
  - One True Prior
     - Pascal's Mugging / leverage prior
     - Second-orderness
     - Anthropics
          - How would an AI decide what to think about QTI?
  - Mindcrime
     - Nonperson predicates (and unblocked neighbor problem)
  - Do What I Don't Know I Mean
  - Philosophical competence

# Foreseen normal difficulties
  - Reproducibility
  - Oracle boxes

# Reflectivity problems
 - Vingean reflection
  - Satisficing / meliorizing / staged maximization / ?
 - Logical decision theory

# Larger research agendas
 - Corrigible reflective unbounded safe genie
  - Bounding the theory
  - Derationalizing the theory (e.g. for a neuromorphic AI)
 - Normative Sovereign
 - Approval-based agents

# Possible future use-cases
 - A carefully designed bounded reflective agent.
 - An overpowered set of known algorithms, heavily constrained in what is authorized, with little recursion.

# Possible escape routes
 - Some cognitively limited task which is relatively safe to carry out at great power, and resolves the larger problem.
  - Newcomers can't invent these well because they don't understand what is a cognitively limited task (e.g., "Tool AI" suggestions).
 - General cognitive tasks that seem boxable and resolve the larger problem.
   - Can you save the world by knowing which consequences of ZF a superintelligence could prove? It's unusually boxable, but what good is it?

3hs.title: Author's guide to Arbital
3hs.clickbait: How to write intuitive, flexible content on Arbital.

3n.title: Arbital "parent" relationship
3n.clickbait: Parent-child relationship between pages implies a strong, inseparable connection.

4j.title: Coordinative AI development hypothetical
4j.clickbait: What would safe AI development look like if we didn't have to worry about anything else?

4w.title: Identifying ambiguous inductions
4w.clickbait: What do a "red strawberry", a "red apple", and a "red cherry" have in common that a "yellow carrot" doesn't?  Are they "red fruits" or "red objects"?

5c.title: Ontology identification problem
5c.clickbait: How do we link an agent's utility function to its model of the world, when we don't know what that model will look like?

5j.title: Distant superintelligences can coerce the most probable environment of your AI
5j.clickbait: Distant superintelligences may be able to hack your local AI, if your AI's preference framework depends on its most probable environment.

5l.title: Complexity of value
5l.clickbait: There's no simple way to describe the goals we want Artificial Intelligences to want.

5t.title: Object-level vs. indirect goals
5t.clickbait: Difference between "give Alice the apple" and "give Alice what she wants".

6q.title: Context disaster
6q.clickbait: Some possible designs cause your AI to behave nicely while developing, and behave a lot less nicely when it's smarter.

6r.title: Methodology of foreseeable difficulties
6r.clickbait: Building a nice AI is likely to be hard enough, and contain enough gotchas that won't show up in the AI's early days, that we need to foresee problems coming in advance.

6s.title: Epistemic and instrumental efficiency
6s.clickbait: An efficient agent never makes a mistake you can predict.  You can never successfully predict a directional bias in its estimates.

6v.title: Mindcrime
6v.clickbait: Might a machine intelligence contain vast numbers of unhappy conscious subprocesses?

6w.title: Task-directed AGI
6w.clickbait: An advanced AI that's meant to pursue a series of limited-scope goals given it by the user.  In Bostrom's terminology, a Genie.
